---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import band from '../data/band.json';
import members from '../data/members.json';
import albums from '../data/albums.json';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="History"
  description="The full story of Cacophony — from formation in 1986 San Francisco to their enduring legacy in neoclassical shred metal."
>
  <main class="history-page">

    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="hero">
      <div class="container">
        <h1>The Story of Cacophony</h1>
        <p class="hero-sub">{band.active_years} &mdash; {band.origin}</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Timeline -->
    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="timeline-heading">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 id="timeline-heading">Timeline</h2>
        <ol class="timeline" role="list">

          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">1986</span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <h3>Formation</h3>
              <p>
                Cacophony was formed in San Francisco, California, by guitarists
                <strong>Marty Friedman</strong> and <strong>Jason Becker</strong> — two of the
                most technically gifted players of their era. The duo had met through mutual
                connections in the Bay Area shred scene and quickly recognised a shared vision
                for combining blistering speed with melodic sophistication.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>

          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">1987</span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <h3>Debut Album: <em>Speed Metal Symphony</em></h3>
              <p>
                Released on <strong>Shrapnel Records</strong>, <em>Speed Metal Symphony</em>
                announced Cacophony to the world. The album showcased the twin-guitar interplay
                of Friedman and Becker alongside vocalist Peter Marrino, keyboardist Jimmy Waldo,
                and drummer Atma Anur. Tracks like &ldquo;The Ninja&rdquo; and the title piece
                became touchstones of the neoclassical shred movement.
              </p>
              <ul class="track-list" aria-label="Speed Metal Symphony track listing">
                {albums[0].tracks.map(t => (
                  <li><span class="track-num">{t.number}.</span> {t.title}</li>
                ))}
              </ul>
            </div>
          </li>

          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">1988</span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <h3>Second Album: <em>Go Off!</em></h3>
              <p>
                The follow-up record, <em>Go Off!</em>, pushed the band&rsquo;s compositional
                ambitions further. With Shane Phillip on vocals and continued contributions from
                Waldo and Anur, the album demonstrated greater dynamic range — balancing technical
                fireworks with melodic depth. &ldquo;Floating World&rdquo; and &ldquo;Imaginary
                Window&rdquo; highlighted the band&rsquo;s growing sophistication.
              </p>
              <ul class="track-list" aria-label="Go Off! track listing">
                {albums[1].tracks.map(t => (
                  <li><span class="track-num">{t.number}.</span> {t.title}</li>
                ))}
              </ul>
            </div>
          </li>

          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">1989</span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <h3>Disbandment</h3>
              <p>
                After three years and two landmark records, Cacophony disbanded in 1989. Both
                Friedman and Becker pursued solo careers and high-profile opportunities that had
                opened as a direct result of Cacophony&rsquo;s impact. Friedman went on to join
                Megadeth, while Becker was recruited by David Lee Roth.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>

          <li class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">1990+</span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <h3>Legacy &amp; After</h3>
              <p>
                In 1990, Jason Becker was diagnosed with ALS (amyotrophic lateral sclerosis).
                The disease eventually robbed him of the ability to play guitar or speak, yet he
                continued composing music using an eye-tracking communication system — a testament
                to his extraordinary musical spirit. Cacophony&rsquo;s two albums remained
                in print and continued to inspire successive generations of guitarists worldwide.
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>

        </ol>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Guitar Virtuosity -->
    <section class="section section-alt" aria-labelledby="style-heading">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 id="style-heading">Guitar Virtuosity &amp; Neoclassical Shred Style</h2>
        <p>
          Cacophony occupied a unique space in the 1980s metal landscape. Friedman and Becker
          shared a grounding in classical harmony and counterpoint that set them apart from peers
          who relied purely on pentatonic blues patterns. Their approach — often described as
          <em>neoclassical shred</em> — drew on Baroque and Romantic-era compositional techniques
          and applied them at breakneck tempos.
        </p>
        <p>
          Key hallmarks of their style included:
        </p>
        <ul class="feature-list">
          <li><strong>Sweep picking</strong> — fluid arpeggios across multiple strings at high speed</li>
          <li><strong>Alternate picking</strong> — precise, metronomic picking for scalar runs</li>
          <li><strong>Harmonic minor and diminished scales</strong> — lending an Eastern and classical flavour</li>
          <li><strong>Two-guitar interplay</strong> — intricate melodic counterpoint between Friedman and Becker</li>
          <li><strong>Dynamic contrast</strong> — moving fluidly between aggressive shred passages and lyrical phrasing</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Marty Friedman developed a highly personal vibrato and an affinity for exotic scales
          influenced by Japanese and Middle Eastern music. Jason Becker, the younger of the two,
          was already being hailed as a prodigy with a tone and expressiveness beyond his years.
          Together they created a sound greater than the sum of its parts.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Members -->
    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="members-heading">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 id="members-heading">The Guitarists</h2>
        <div class="members-grid">
          {members.map(member => (
            <article class="member-card">
              <h3>{member.name}</h3>
              <p class="member-role">{member.role}</p>
              <p>{member.bio}</p>
              <a
                href={member.wikipedia_url}
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                class="wiki-link"
              >
                Wikipedia &rarr;
              </a>
            </article>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Influences & Legacy -->
    <section class="section section-alt" aria-labelledby="legacy-heading">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 id="legacy-heading">Influences &amp; Legacy</h2>

        <h3>Influences</h3>
        <p>
          Both Friedman and Becker cited a wide range of influences that shaped Cacophony&rsquo;s
          distinctive sound:
        </p>
        <ul class="feature-list">
          <li><strong>Yngwie Malmsteen</strong> — pioneer of neoclassical metal guitar who established the template both men built upon</li>
          <li><strong>Johann Sebastian Bach &amp; Niccolò Paganini</strong> — classical composers whose harmonic language permeated Cacophony&rsquo;s compositions</li>
          <li><strong>Eddie Van Halen</strong> — revolutionary rock guitarist who redefined what was possible on the instrument</li>
          <li><strong>Japanese &amp; Eastern music</strong> — exotic scales and melodic sensibilities, particularly influential on Friedman</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Legacy</h3>
        <p>
          Despite their brief existence, Cacophony left an indelible mark on heavy metal and
          guitar music at large. They helped codify the neoclassical shred genre, demonstrating
          that technical virtuosity and compositional depth were not mutually exclusive. Their
          two albums on Shrapnel Records remain essential listening for students of guitar
          and metal history alike.
        </p>
        <p>
          Marty Friedman&rsquo;s subsequent work with Megadeth — including the landmark
          <em>Rust in Peace</em> (1990) — brought neoclassical sensibilities to a mainstream
          metal audience. Jason Becker&rsquo;s personal story of perseverance in the face of
          ALS became an inspiration far beyond the guitar world, immortalised in the 2012
          documentary <em>Jason Becker: Not Dead Yet</em>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Cacophony&rsquo;s influence continues to reverberate through the playing of guitarists
          who cite Friedman and Becker as formative inspirations, ensuring that the band&rsquo;s
          brief but brilliant flame burns on.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* ── Layout ── */
  .history-page {
    min-height: calc(100vh - var(--nav-height));
  }

  .container {
    max-width: 860px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 0 1.5rem;
  }

  /* ── Hero ── */
  .hero {
    background: linear-gradient(160deg, var(--color-surface) 0%, var(--color-bg) 100%);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding: 4rem 0 3rem;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .hero h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3.5rem);
    font-weight: 800;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .hero-sub {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
  }

  /* ── Sections ── */
  .section {
    padding: 4rem 0;
  }

  .section-alt {
    background-color: var(--color-surface);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .section h2 {
    font-size: 1.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .section h3 {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem;
  }

  .section p {
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  /* ── Timeline ── */
  .timeline {
    list-style: none;
    position: relative;
    padding-left: 0;
  }

  .timeline::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 5.5rem;
    top: 0;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 2px;
    background: var(--color-border);
  }

  .timeline-item {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 5rem 1fr;
    gap: 0 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
  }

  .timeline-item::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: calc(5.5rem - 5px);
    top: 0.35rem;
    width: 10px;
    height: 10px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--color-accent);
    border: 2px solid var(--color-bg);
  }

  .timeline-year {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    padding-top: 0.2rem;
    text-align: right;
  }

  .timeline-content h3 {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  /* ── Track List ── */
  .track-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(200px, 1fr));
    gap: 0.25rem 1.5rem;
    margin: 0.75rem 0 0;
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    background: rgba(200, 168, 75, 0.05);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 6px;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .track-list li {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.4rem;
  }

  .track-num {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    flex-shrink: 0;
    font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums;
  }

  /* ── Feature List ── */
  .feature-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0.75rem 0 1rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.5rem;
  }

  .feature-list li {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    position: relative;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  .feature-list li::before {
    content: '▸';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  /* ── Members Grid ── */
  .members-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: 1.5rem;
  }

  .member-card {
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 1.5rem;
  }

  .member-card h3 {
    margin-top: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-size: 1.15rem;
  }

  .member-role {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem !important;
  }

  .wiki-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
  }

  /* ── Responsive ── */
  @media (max-width: 560px) {
    .timeline::before {
      left: 4rem;
    }

    .timeline-item {
      grid-template-columns: 3.5rem 1fr;
    }

    .timeline-item::before {
      left: calc(4rem - 5px);
    }

    .timeline-year {
      font-size: 0.8rem;
    }
  }
</style>
